  "footnotes": [
    "Varangian trade routes: Norse traders and warriors travelled through Novgorod and down the Dnieper ('from the Varangians to the Greeks'), founding or ruling early Rus cities; Rurik is traditionally credited with founding the Rus dynasty in Novgorod (c.862).",
    "Tatar Yoke (1237–1480): Mongol/Tatar suzerainty over Russian principalities; princes received patents (yarlyk) from the Khan; the term is contested by historians — Novgorod was never occupied.",
    "Time of Troubles (1598–1613): Period of dynastic crisis, famine, foreign intervention (Polish and Swedish), and civil war following the death of Tsar Fyodor I; ended with the election of Mikhail Romanov.",
    "Conquest of Siberia: Russian Cossacks and traders crossed the Urals and reached the Pacific within 60 years (1581–1639), one of history's fastest territorial expansions; the indigenous population declined sharply due to disease and violence.",
    "Pugachev Rebellion (1773–1775): The largest Cossack-peasant revolt in Russian history, led by Yemelyan Pugachev who claimed to be Tsar Peter III; suppressed by Catherine II.",
    "Leningrad Siege (1941–1944): 872-day siege by Nazi Germany and Finland; approximately 800,000 civilians died, mostly from starvation; one of the deadliest sieges in history.",
    "Gulag: Soviet system of forced-labour camps operating 1918–1960 (peak in Stalin era); an estimated 14–18 million passed through; concentrated heavily in Siberia and the Far North."
  ]
